Daud Olatunji, Abeokuta Ogun State Governor, Dapo Abiodun, has presented a budget of N339bn for the 2021 fiscal year to the State Assembly. Of this amount, N162bn is for recurrent expenditure while N177bn is being proposed for capital expenditure. The governor christened the budget, “Budget of Recovery and Sustainability.” According to him, the budget is expected to be financed with N119bn to be generated internally and N59bn expected as receipts from the federation account. Internal and external loans are expected to account for N142bn. Total overhead cost for Ministries, Departments and Agencies is expected to gulp N50bn representing an increase of N11bn from N39bn in budgeted for 2020. He told the legislators that his administration was proposing to spend N28.4bn for debt service representing an increase of N13bn from N15.7bn in the outgoing year. For sectoral allocations, the governor proposed the sum of N58bn, for education while N75bn is to be spent on economic affairs. N49bn was earmarked for general services, while health is to gulp N35bn. The sum of N28bn is being proposed for housing and community amenities. He said, “The proposed N339 billion expenditure comprises the recurrent of N162bn and Capital of N177bn. We have been able to achieve a 52 percent capital expenditure as dictated by best practices to drive our developmental objectives. “Substantial part of the 2021 recurrent cost estimate is allocated to paying salaries and overheads in MDAs providing these critical public services.” Earlier in his welcome address, the Speaker of the Ogun State House of Assembly, Olakunle Oluomo, promised that the house will give the proposal the attention it deserves. Copyright PUNCH.
